Title:
EVENSTAR – KernelToUserInjector (v3.0.0)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This repository contains sample Windows kernel-mode driver code that injects code into a user-mode process using Asynchronous Procedure Calls (APCs).  
- It focuses on performing kernel-to-user injection by locating a target process/thread (including a thread in an alertable wait state), mapping/providing a user virtual address (UVA) payload buffer, and queueing both a special kernel APC and a regular user-mode APC.  
- The project explicitly targets modern Windows (tested on Windows 11 25H2) and is updated to evade additional ETW “Threat Intelligence” sensors related to kernel APC injection telemetry.  
- It is primarily useful for red team operators, malware developers, and security researchers studying kernel-assisted injection and EDR/ETW detection surfaces.  
- It’s interesting because it demonstrates a kernel-originated injection path and references known work on bypassing Microsoft-Windows-Threat-Intelligence APC injection sensors.

Technical Focus:
- Windows kernel-mode driver development (C, CPL0)  
- APC internals (special kernel APC vs user-mode APC)  
- Kernel-to-user code injection workflow (PID/TID targeting, alertable threads)  
- ETW / Microsoft-Windows-Threat-Intelligence sensor evasion considerations  
- Windows 11 injection/detection behavior validation

Use Cases:
- Implementing and testing kernel-assisted user-mode payload execution via APCs  
- Researching/replicating ETW Threat Intelligence detections for APC injection  
- Building lab PoCs to evaluate EDR visibility into kernel-originated injection  
- Studying thread state requirements (alertable waits) for user APC delivery

Keywords:
Windows kernel driver, kernel-to-user injection, APC injection, Asynchronous Procedure Call, special kernel APC, user-mode APC, KeInsertQueueApc, alertable wait, PID, TID, user virtual address, ETW, Microsoft-Windows-Threat-Intelligence, EDR evasion, Windows 11, Defender for Endpoint, telemetry bypass, Blackbone, KernelInjector